tus as an \"accredited investor\" under Regulation D of the Securities Act of 1933, providing specific criteria they meet (income thresholds, net worth requirements, or entity qualifications). Include representations regarding the subscriber's investment intent, acknowledgment that the securities are not registered and cannot be freely transferred, understanding of illiquidity and lock-up periods, and capacity to bear the economic risk of loss. Draft comprehensive risk acknowledgments covering market risk, lack of liquidity, potential for total loss, reliance on management, conflicts of interest, and regulatory risks specific to the fund's investment strategy.\n\nEstablish clear conditions precedent to the fund's obligation to accept the subscription, including satisfactory completion of know-your-customer (KYC) and anti-money laundering (AML) due diligence, receipt of all required documentation (W-9 or W-8 forms, accreditation verification, entity formation documents if applicable), and approval by the fund's general partner or investment committee. Specify that the subscription becomes binding only upon written acceptance by the fund.\n\nDetail the payment mechanics with precision, including acceptable payment methods (wire transfer, check, in-kind contributions if permitted), wire instructions, payment deadlines relative to the subscription date or acceptance notice, and procedures for handling insufficient funds or failed transfers. Describe the closing process, including when the subscriber will be admitted to the fund, when capital will be called if using a drawdown structure, and when the subscriber will receive confirmation of their ownership interest.\n\n## Legal Framework and Compliance\n\nThe governing law provision should specify the state law that governs the agreement's interpretation and enforcement, typically matching the fund's jurisdiction of formation or principal place of business. Include a mandatory arbitration or forum selection clause specify